SIMPLE: theorem
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Theorem
<hw>The"o*rem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>theorema</ets>, Gr. <?/ a sight, speculation, theory, theorem, fr.
<?/ to look at, <?/ a spectator: cf. F.
<ets>th⟦eacute⟧or⟦egrave⟧me</ets>. See <er>Theory</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is considered and established as a
principle; hence, sometimes, a rule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not theories, but <qex>theorems</qex> (<?/), the intelligible
products of contemplation, intellectual objects in the mind, and of and
for the mind exclusively.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By the <qex>theorems</qex>,⟦br⟧
Which your polite and terser gallants practice,⟦br⟧
I re-refine the court, and civilize⟦br⟧
Their barbarous natures.</q> <rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>A statement of a principle to be
demonstrated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>theorem</xex> is something to be proved, and is
thus distinguished from a <xex>problem</xex>, which is something to be
solved. In analysis, the term is sometimes applied to a rule, especially
a rule or statement of relations expressed in a formula or by symbols;
<as>as, the binomial <ex>theorem</ex>; Taylor's <ex>theorem</ex></as>.
See the Note under <er>Proposition</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 5.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Binomial theorem</b></col>. <fld>(Math.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Binomial</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Negative theorem</b></col>,
<cd>a theorem which expresses the impossibility of any assertion.</cd>
-- <col><b>Particular theorem</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a
theorem which extends only to a particular quantity.</cd> --
<col><b>Theorem of Pappus</b></col>. <fld>(Math.)</fld> <cd>See
<cref>Centrobaric method</cref>, under <er>Centrobaric</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Universal theorem</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a theorem
which extends to any quantity without restriction.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Theorem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Theorem
<hw>The"o*rem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To formulate into a
theorem.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Theorematical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Theorematic</ent>⟦br⟧
